      "side": 1,
      "message": "[🟡 Suggestions] Line 386: scheduleBeacon() acquires stateMutex and then calls asio::steady_timer::expires_after(), which can synchronously cancel an existing wait and cause the previous handler to run inline on some executors/Asio configurations. Because the handler can call scheduleBeacon() again, this risks lock re-entry/deadlock or subtle ordering issues. Keep timer manipulation on the socket/event-loop context without holding stateMutex, or reduce the lock scope to only reading shutdown state before arming the timer.\n```suggestion\n    {\n        std::lock_guard lk(stateMutex);\n        if (isShutdown_)\n            return;\n    }\n    beaconIntervalTimer_.expires_after(BEACON_INTERVAL);\n```",
      "revId": "e5c3bf0c5226ed5846cb16ac29bfe281f888a909",
